

creat a github repository
Install the dependencies - requirement.txt
create .env and add configurable paths
create the docs_dir folder - for the documents
create the src folder (This contains all the source code)
create  folders inside the src (agents, backend, frontend, rag_doc_ingestion)
create __init__.py file inside the folders
In the gitignore folder, uncomment .idea
Add the vector db to the git ignore

Next
Document Ingestion
1. RAG document ingestion
- Create a config folder inside the rag-doc-ingestion
- Create a new file inside the 'config' folder - doc_ingestion_settings
- add the documents ingestion settings on the file
- Add another file 'ingest_doc' inside the 'rag_doc_ingestion' directory
- ingest_doc = will have the code to build your vector database
- Run this script --- python -m src.rag_doc_ingestion.ingest_docs

push to github
git add .
git status
git commit -m "description"
git push origin main

Next
Create the Agent ie build the RAG Agent
Creat a RAG query tool that will connect to vector database and give answers to the relevant
response for the user query
A crewai agent will be using this tool
- create the 'agents_src' folder and add "agents,config,llm,task,tools" folders inside
- In the 'agents' folder create the agent setting "question_answer_agent"
- In the 'tool' folder creat the 'rag_qa_tool' file : The tool will be used by the agent
- Create 'llm' folder inside the src directory. Create 'get_llm' and 'llm_configuration' inside the folder
- llm_configuration is used to configure llm. You can add additional llm and adjust/update. Different agentscan use different models
- create the 'tasks' folder inside the src. Add 'question_answer_task' file inside the task folders
- create the 'crew.py' and 'check_crew.py' file inside tools
- check_crew.py is used to test if the crew is working or not

Next
Create the backend and frontend folders and codes
-run this script -- python -m src.backend_src.main
- --This will start the api
- check the api using -- http://localhost:8000/docs

Next
- Create a Docker file - add the configurations
- Create the 'start.sh' file and add the configurations
** Note: DO not add your API key while building the Docker image

Next
- Ensure docker is running on your system
- Deploy Docker using the steps on 'deploy_on_docker_steps'
- Create a Docker container

